"script": "Look closely at a zipper, and the only moving part is that little slider. So how does pulling one tab lock two rows of teeth shut? You see, every tooth has a hook on top and a hollow on the bottom. As the slider glides up, its Y-shaped channel forces each tooth sideways into the gap of the one across from it. Then the hook snaps into the hollow, and the tooth behind it holds the whole thing locked. And this is why one single broken tooth ruins the entire zipper for good.",
